{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488947"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:03:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:03:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"581"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/581"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.56,0.08,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56441"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/581"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41996"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15854"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56441"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a three-week history of troublesome urinary frequency and difficulty in starting and stopping the stream of urine. His medical history includes Parkinson\u0027s disease, diabetes mellitus, and ischaemic heart disease. His medications are levodopa/carbidopa, trihexyphenidyl, metformin, aspirin, and lisinopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis case notes record that his medications were recently adjusted because of worsening symptoms related to his Parkinson\u0027s disease. His wife had reported that the resting tremor in his hands was becoming more of a problem, and he was finding it difficult to do simple things such as making his morning cup of tea. However, his urinary problems are now the main nuisance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of his medications is most likely to be contributing to his urinary problems?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Levodopa/carbidopa","Trihexyphenidyl","Aspirin","Metformin","Lisinopril"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EParkinson\u0027s disease is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder characterised by tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia, and postural instability. Management often involves a combination of medications to address these motor symptoms. While levodopa/carbidopa is the cornerstone of treatment, adjunctive therapies like anticholinergics may be used to target specific symptoms such as tremor. However, these can have side effects, including urinary retention, which must be carefully managed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario describes a patient with Parkinson\u0027s disease who is suffering from urinary retention, which can be due to a variety of causes including benign prostatic hyperplasia, neurogenic bladder, and medications. Among the medications listed, the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s urinary retention is \u003Cstrong\u003Etrihexyphenidyl\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrihexyphenidyl\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticholinergic medication often used as an adjunctive therapy in Parkinson\u0027s disease to help control tremors and rigidity. Anticholinergic medications can lead to urinary retention by inhibiting detrusor muscle contraction in the bladder, which can interfere with normal voiding mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevodopa/carbidopa\u003C/strong\u003E, the first-line treatment for Parkinson\u0027s disease, does not typically cause urinary retention. It is primarily used to manage motor symptoms by replenishing dopamine levels in the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin, metformin, and lisinopril\u003C/strong\u003E are common medications used for cardiovascular disease and diabetes and do not typically lead to urinary retention. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trihexyphenidyl, an anticholinergic medication, can cause urinary retention in patients with Parkinson\u0027s disease by inhibiting detrusor muscle contraction in the bladder.","Parkinson\u0027s disease is a neurodegenerative disorder characterised by tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia, and postural instability.","Management of Parkinson\u0027s disease often involves a combination of medications to address motor symptoms, including levodopa/carbidopa and anticholinergics."],"references":["Hayes M. Parkinson\u0027s Disease and Parkinsonism. The American Journal of Medicine. 2019;132(7):802-807.","Jilani TN, Sabir S, Patel P, et al. Trihexyphenidyl. [Updated 2024 Jun 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519488/","Waller S, Williams L, Morales-Brice\u00f1o H, Fung VS. The initial diagnosis and management of Parkinson\u0027s disease. Aust J Gen Pract. 2021 Nov;50(11):793-800. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-07-21-6087. PMID: 34713282."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41996"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"581"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41996"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-20T19:15:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-20T20:04:20